<h1>Good Morning!</h1>

<p>Hi there, my name’s Zachary Nicoll, but you can me Zach. I’m currently over at <a href="http://intelity.com/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer">Intelity</a> working on all sorts of cool things. I love what I do, but I also love life and everything that goes along with it. Yes, I’m a software developer, but more importantly I’m a husband, a (soon-to-be) father, a diver, and a gamer. Perhaps even more paramount to the core of who I am, I’m also a strong believer in oxford commas.</p>

<h2>My Sweet Skills</h2>

<p>I’m primarily a front end web developer. Like, real front end. Not that fake front end business that people have started calling “front end” just because you can do it with JavaScript (looking at you, Node). More specifically, CSS is my jam. I’ve never used a CSS framework to do anything and I don’t plan to. I suppose it’s worth mentioning that I can also do just about anything in JavaScript, and honestly, that’s probably where most of my time is spent on the day-to-day.</p>

<p>My roots are in Haml, Sass, CoffeeScript, and Ruby on Rails; but as time went on, I started favoring the UI side of things and picked up Ember.js.  I now work with either HTML, Sass, and/or Ember on a daily basis. I do dabble occasionally in Swift as well, but not very often these days. And yeah, like everyone else who’s honest with themselves, I too miss CoffeeScript.</p>

<p>Here’s a much more boring list, in <span title="alphabetical, because I’m not a monster">no particular</span> order: Bash, C#, Erb, Git, Illustrator, Photoshop, Regex, and SQL. These are the things I can do/use to varying degrees, but definitely not where my passions are. I’ve also used things like ActionScript, ColdFusion, Flex, and PHP in the past, but I’m quite certain I’ve forgotten almost everything I ever knew about them.</p>

<h2>How’d I get those sweet skills?</h2>

<p>I graduated from <a href="https://www.fullsail.edu/degrees/web-design-and-development-bachelor" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer">Full Sail University</a> in 2011 with a BS in Web Design & Development. They gave me a pretty solid foundation in full stack development, but I preferred front end right from the start. Right before I graduated, I landed a job in Colorado as a front end developer and haven’t looked back.</p>

<p>I only had that first job for a few short months, because <a href="https://twitter.com/alyssanicoll" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer">my wife</a> decided she wanted to do what I did. So, I got a new job in Orlando as a web developer, and back to Florida (and Full Sail) we went. I filled many roles and positions there, but I always stuck to front end development when I could. Be sure to check out the {{link-to "projects" "projects"}} page for details.</p>

